<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-200-175 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 542 767</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 15 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Big Blue bites bullet, kills Displaywriter. (IBM discontinues wordprocessing software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Product discontinuation).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   DisplayWrite (Word processing software) (Product discontinuation).andO;Topic:     Word processing softwareProduct DiscontinuationCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****BIG BLUE BITES BULLET, KILLS DISPLAYWRITER 03/15/91 ARMONK, NEW YORK,U.S.A., 1991 MAR 15 (NB) -- IBM has announced that it will drop its long-timeword processor DisplayWrite in favor of a very fast program being developedby XyWrite's creator, XyQuest, Inc.andM;Although once a major player in the word processing field because it was inthe market from the beginning, IBM's DisplayWrite is now a very antiquatedprogram that holds only about five percent of the market versus nearly 62percent for WordPerfect and 18 percent for Microsoft Word.andM;The new program, to be named Signature, will replace both DisplayWrite andXyWrite IV with a graphical user interface word processor that users can alsorun in a text or character- based mode.andM;Computerworld reports that IBM will support Displaywrite 4.2 and 5.0 untilthe end of 1992.andM;Faced with a massive installed base of Word and WordPerfect, some industryobservers have pointed out that this move by IBM is about seven years toolate.andM;One editor of a government-related publication pointed out that, althoughXyWrite is very fast, his experience had been that, while they could teachnew employees simple editing operations on XyWrite in a few hours, anythingbeyond basic deleting and block moves are very difficult to learn and thatall the pull-down menu systems he had tested for XyWrite were veryinadequate.andM;(John McCormick/19910315)</TEXT></DOC>